About the Project

Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is a progressive disease that destroys memory and other important mental functions. It is the 6th leading cause of death in the US, and it does not have a cure. The latter fact strongly affects a family of a newly diagnosed with AD patient. Exploring the landscape of ongoing clinical trials targeting AD, is the next step families take to assess possible treatment options. Clinicaltrials.gov is a database of clinical studies conducted around the world and is a great place to start exploring experimental treatment possibilities. It has a user-friendly interface and provides extensive amount of clinical trials information. However, it could be overwhelming for someone without special training to dive through the vast amounts of tabulated information available at clinicaltrials.gov. A web-based visualization tool, which summarizes Alzheimer`s Disease study data sourced from clinicaltrials.gov, could be a useful tool for those families impacted by the illness, and seeking a quick visual reference guide on Alzheimer’s Disease research, past and present.

Data and Methods

The data were obtained by downloading all results associated with a search for “alzheimer” on the website clinicaltrials.gov. Data were accessed on 11/09/2017. All studies associated with the search term were included regardless of whether the study had previously been completed, terminated, or other enrollment status factors. File Names [Imaani]

The data were obtained by downloading all results associated with a search for “alzheimer” on the website clinicaltrials.gov. Data were accessed on 11/09/2017. All studies associated with the search term were included regardless of enrollment status factors; whether the study was completed, terminated, or is actively recruiting participants, all were included. The data used in analyses are available in the Data file on the github page and the primary data file used in analysis is called SearchResultsTable.csv.

Additional variables of interest were obtained by downloading all the data from each webpage associated with all studies returned in the original “alzheimer” search. These data were also accessed on 11/09/2017. Source code for extracting these variables are available in the file Extracting_data_across_all_xml_files.Rmd also on the github page. An additional dataset called alzheimers_data containing all variables associated with each study identified during the “alzheimer” search.

The datasets SearchResultsTable.csv and alzheimers_data contain largely overlapping variables. The dataset SearchResultsTable.csv is generally more processed, particularly for natural language variables. However, alzheimers_data contains several variables not available in SearchResultsTable.csv that an interested future researcher may access.

Summary Statistics [Faith/Volha?]

The main dataset contained 1,771 records corresponding to all studies on Alzheimer’s Disease registered at the ClinicalTrials.gov website with study start dates from April 1, 2014 to September 6, 2017. We restricted our analysis dataset to the 928 studies with study sites in the United States. The earliest study on record began on April 1, 2017.

The number of study sites within the United States ranged from 1 to 219.

Exploratory analysis [Volha will combine three figures and an intercative data table]

Gantt chart was created for those studies with available starting and ending dates, to visualize the landscape of Alzheimer’s Disease clinical trials over time.

Interactive lineplot was created for those studies with available age eligibility criteria, where a line represents age eligibility for a particular study against the number of subjects enrolled in a study.

Alzheimer’s Disease is a disease of an older population, and clinical trials in the past were targeting these subjects. However, since many hundreds of clinical trials failed in finding a cure, research has shifted to include younger populations as well, with the hope of preventing Alzheimer’s before the major damage to the brain is done in the later stages of the disease.

Discussion

The Shiny dashboard created in this project creates a simple and user-friendly format for interested parties, including physicians and researchers with less statistical knowledge, as well as the data-savvy patient, to explore trends in Alzheimer’s-related clinical trials.

Possible future directions for this project include updating the Shiny dashboard so that it interacts in real-time with the clinicaltrials.gov website. This would allow the data in the dashboard to continue to provide the most up-to-date information to the user, and would prevent the dashboard from becoming obsolete over time. Currently, a dashboard such as this would need to be maintained with daily updates of the datasets, but that can be changed if it were to be developed further. For example, rate-limiting from the GoogleMaps API prevents the user from making too many live calls for coordinate data, and can render the mapping feature ineffective, but this limiting does not exist in the paid version.

Other possible future directions include incorporating additional variables so that the user can gain a more complete picture of the available data. Another area of possible expansion might include developing a platform for the user to perform simple statistical tests on the data from within the project website.
